div.div: An alignment match is a pair of two token-substrings of source code. One part of that pair - the query-document side - is a part of the query-document. The other side - the fragment side - is a part of an answer fragment. The levenshtein distance of the two halves of an alignment match is a parameter for the alignment step.

The aim of the pipeline is to find individual reuses of a pattern. Therefore a search result must show such a suspected usage. A search result is a collection of alignment matches with one answer fragment. The alignment matches in a search result are non-overlapping and occur in the query document in a structural order that matches the structural order of the answer fragment.
Search results are initially generated by the code block structure filtering step and then further refined by steps like the identifier word similarity filter.
